<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-25T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-25T22:00:00-05:00" n="505" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d505">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker, Charles</persName>/42:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-26T11:00:00+08:00">March 26, 1932—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 26—3:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Hankow’s 45, March 24, 2 p.m. I question the propriety of our suggesting
                            that flood relief wheat be used to obtain <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName>’s release. If the
                            Chinese Government wishes to use it for that purpose it can do so on its
                            own initiative.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>